1 CONC Mary Dehn was adopted by Charles W. Tauscher and his wife
1 CONT
0 @N2@ NOTE
1 CONC Vici was adopted by her step-father Richard Cowell.
1 CONT
0 @N3@ NOTE
1 CONC According to Dean Stelmach, he never knew his father  Gary Kehle. He states his father was in prison when Dean was born. Dean's mother was 16 at the time.
1 CONT
1 CONT Dean states that when Judy died that Ronald Stelmach left him with his grandparents Leroy and Mary Villone. He states that Mary was hooked on prescription medications at the time and that his great-grandmother Ethyl Carrier Anton kept him most o
1 CONC f the time.
0 @N4@ NOTE
1 CONC Her Death Certificate states she was born in El Paso, Texas and the census states she was born in Mexico.
1 CONT
0 @N5@ NOTE
1 CONC Find a Grave is incorrect with the parent connections. They have him connected to his aunt and uncle who also had a child named James.
0 @N6@ NOTE
1 CONC In 1930 Peter's parents were going through a bitter divorce and sold their property in Niagara Falls. The family split up during this time.
1 CONT
1 CONT Peter's father Peter Paul Villone shows up living with the grandparents in the 1930 Niagara Falls Census.
1 CONT
1 CONT I have yet to find Jannette Heintz Villone and her children showing up in the 1930 census.
1 CONT
0 @N7@ NOTE
1 CONC Mabel Van Volkenburg never married nor had children.
0 @N8@ NOTE
1 CONC Per my father Joseph Cox:
1 CONT
1 CONT He states that his father, Joseph Lindley McGriff, left when he was very young. His mother, Rebecca Curiel McGriff Cox,  had his name surname changed to Cox which was her current husband's surname.
1 CONT
1 CONT Milo Cox was Rebecca's husband at the time and he adopted Joseph. Joseph states that Milo was abusive and he left at the age of 17 to join the military.
1 CONT
1 CONT Joseph wanted to change his name back to McGriff before joining the military. He went to the courthouse in El Paso, Tx, to get a copy of his original birth certificate. They would not give him a copy because Rebecca had the court to seal the recor
1 CONC d.
1 CONT
1 CONT I found the Texas, U.S., Naturalization Record which shows that his Birth Name is Joseph Lindly McGriff.
1 CONT
1 CONT On October 30, 2022, I provided the document to my father.
1 CONT
0 @N9@ NOTE
0 @N10@ NOTE
1 CONC Died in Infancy according to Harold F Baker.
0 @N11@ NOTE
1 CONC Harold F. Baker in his book  A Journey in Time Volume II, page 155 states Amandon Baker died November 9, 1890. There is no source in his book to prove this.
0 @N12@ NOTE
1 CONC Most of the documents have her maiden last name listed as Buskirk. Her daughter Emma's Marriage certificate lists it as Van Buskirk.
0 @N13@ NOTE
1 CONC Raymond McGriff was listed in the 1959 Census as living in a Veterans Home.
0 @N14@ NOTE
1 CONC Mary was living with her mother Mary Dutra and stepfather Frank Sneed in 1940. She was listed as Mary Rae Sneed on the 1940 census.
0 @N15@ NOTE
1 CONC Born premature and the baby only lived a few hours.
0 @N16@ NOTE
1 CONC There is a lot of false narratives on Richard McGriff. All I have at this point are other trees telling me this Richard McGriff is part of the family line.
1 CONT
1 CONT Other people's trees list a marriage certificate of a daughter being married in Alabama at Richard McGriff's Home. This was years after Richard McGriff was dead and this is also not the same Richard McGriff. That Richard McGriff was married to Sar
1 CONC ah Kind and that family resided in Alabama.
0 @N17@ NOTE
1 CONC Tazewell County History details an interesting story stating in 1775 the John McGriff family was attacked by Indians and he shot one of them. His son was kidnapped by the Indians and later escaped. There is no proof this is the same John Mcgriff
1 CONC , but it is possible.
0 @N18@ NOTE
1 CONC Mr. Martin had been in ill health since he and Mrs. Martin was seriously injured in an auto accident on Dec. 27, 1950. He and his wife spent one year in Columbus Hospital after the accident.
1 CONT
1 CONT He was of the Brotherhood of Railroader Trainmen. Surviving is his wife. The former Lillian Hientz.
0 @N19@ NOTE
1 CONC Lloyd S Baker changed his name, moved to Canada, joined the military during WWI, and remained in Canada to start a family of his own.
0 @N20@ NOTE
1 CONC John's 1st wife is unknown. The NY County Marriage records states he was a widower and Mildred Baker was his second wife.
1 CONT
1 CONT John's mother died when he was 7 leaving his grandfather Sylvester to raise John. Sylvester died in 1901 when John was 12.
1 CONT
0 @N21@ NOTE
1 CONC According to his brother Henry Palmerter, the first name is spelled Denice and not Dennis. He states that people made fun of his name.
